## Welcome to TEN

[Permalink: Welcome to TEN](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#welcome-to-ten)

TEN is a comprehensive open-source ecosystem for creating, customizing, and deploying real-time conversational AI agents with multimodal capabilities including voice, vision, and avatar interactions.

TEN includes the [TEN Framework](https://github.com/ten-framework/ten-framework), [TEN VAD](https://github.com/ten-framework/ten-vad), [TEN Turn Detection](https://github.com/ten-framework/ten-turn-detection) and [TEN Portal](https://github.com/ten-framework/portal). See [TEN Ecosystem](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#ten-ecosystem) for more details.

#### Step ⓶ - Build agent examples in VM

[Permalink: Step ⓶ - Build agent examples in VM](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#step----build-agent-examples-in-vm)

##### 1\. Clone the repo, `cd` into `ai_agents`, and create a `.env` file from `.env.example`

[Permalink: 1. Clone the repo, cd into ai_agents, and create a .env file from .env.example](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#1-clone-the-repo-cd-into-ai_agents-and-create-a-env-file-from-envexample)

```
cd ai_agents
cp ./.env.example ./.env
```

##### 2\. Set up the Agora App ID and App Certificate in `.env`

[Permalink: 2. Set up the Agora App ID and App Certificate in .env](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#2-set-up-the-agora-app-id-and-app-certificate-in-env)

```
AGORA_APP_ID=
AGORA_APP_CERTIFICATE=

# In case you are running the default voice-assistant example
# Deepgram (required for speech-to-text)
DEEPGRAM_API_KEY=your_deepgram_api_key_here

# OpenAI (required for language model)
OPENAI_API_KEY=your_openai_api_key_here
OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-4o

# ElevenLabs (required for text-to-speech)
ELEVENLABS_TTS_KEY=your_elevenlabs_api_key_here
```

##### 3\. Start agent development containers

[Permalink: 3. Start agent development containers](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#3-start-agent-development-containers)

```
docker compose up -d
```

##### 4\. Enter the container

[Permalink: 4. Enter the container](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#4-enter-the-container)

```
docker exec -it ten_agent_dev bash
```

##### 5\. Build the agent with the default example (~5-8 min)

[Permalink: 5. Build the agent with the default example (~5-8 min)](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#5-build-the-agent-with-the-default-example-5-8-min)

Check the `agents/examples` folder for additional samples.
Start with one of these defaults:

```
# use the chained voice assistant
cd agents/examples/voice-assistant

# or use the speech-to-speech voice assistant in real time
cd agents/examples/voice-assistant-realtime
```

##### 6\. Start the web server

[Permalink: 6. Start the web server](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#6-start-the-web-server)

Run `task build` if you changed any local source code. This step is required for compiled languages (for example, TypeScript or Go) and not needed for Python.

```
task install
task run
```

##### 7\. Access the agent

[Permalink: 7. Access the agent](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#7-access-the-agent)

Once the agent example is running, you can access the following interfaces:

#### Step ⓷ - Customize your agent

[Permalink: Step ⓷ - Customize your agent](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#step----customize-your-agent)

1. Open [localhost:49483](http://localhost:49483/).
2. Right-click the STT, LLM, and TTS extensions.
3. Open their properties and enter the corresponding API keys.
4. Right-click the canvas and select **Manage Apps** to open the Apps Manager.
5. Under **Actions**, click ▶ to run the app.
6. Select **Run with TEN Agent**, then click **Run**.

### Deploying with Docker

[Permalink: Deploying with Docker](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#deploying-with-docker)

Once you have customized your agent (either by using the TMAN Designer or editing `property.json` directly), you can deploy it by creating a release Docker image for your service.

##### Release as Docker image

[Permalink: Release as Docker image](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#release-as-docker-image)

**Note**: The following commands need to be executed outside of any Docker container.

###### Build image

[Permalink: Build image](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#build-image)

```
cd ai_agents
docker build -f agents/examples/<example-name>/Dockerfile -t example-app .
```

###### Run

[Permalink: Run](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#run)

```
docker run --rm -it --env-file .env -p 3000:3000 example-app
```

[![divider](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/2340896/505543693-c763ffa6-0b9f-4599-9e50-8ea97021e412.png?jwt=eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9..5qwZe3lD9pQrgYr461eG9WKpLgC_87WnA1jfMLqPRy8)](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/2340896/505543693-c763ffa6-0b9f-4599-9e50-8ea97021e412.png?jwt=eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9..5qwZe3lD9pQrgYr461eG9WKpLgC_87WnA1jfMLqPRy8)

### Deploying with other cloud services

[Permalink: Deploying with other cloud services](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#deploying-with-other-cloud-services)

You can split the deployment into two pieces when you want to host TEN on providers such as [Vercel](https://vercel.com/) or [Netlify](https://www.netlify.com/).

1. Run the TEN backend on any container-friendly platform (a VM with Docker, Fly.io, Render, ECS, Cloud Run, or similar). Use the example Docker image without modifying it and expose port `8080` from that service.

2. Deploy only the frontend to Vercel or Netlify. Point the project root to `ai_agents/agents/examples/<example>/frontend`, run `pnpm install` (or `bun install`) followed by `pnpm build` (or `bun run build`), and keep the default `.next` output directory.

3. Configure environment variables in your hosting dashboard so that `AGENT_SERVER_URL` points to the backend URL, and add any `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` keys the UI needs (for example, Agora credentials you surface to the browser).

4. Ensure your backend accepts requests from the frontend origin — via open CORS or by using the built-in proxy middleware.


With this setup, the backend handles long-running worker processes, while the hosted frontend simply forwards API traffic to it.

[![](https://camo.githubusercontent.com/3b0724fd7f2930cebfa134bfc45bd58ebc90f5dfbf2dfeb2b4cf8916ac6f9add/68747470733a2f2f696d672e736869656c64732e696f2f62616467652f2d4261636b5f746f5f746f702d677261793f7374796c653d666c61742d737175617265)](https://github.com/Neozhou168/ten-framework#readme-top)
